---
import FeaturePageLayout from "../../layouts/FeaturePageLayout.astro";
import DownloadButton from "../../components/button/DownloadButton";
import DownloadMuseHubButton from "../../components/button/DownloadMuseHubButton";
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import AudacityMockUp from "../../assets/img/HeroBannerImage.webp";
---

<FeaturePageLayout
  title="Free Noise Reduction Tool – Remove Background Noise | Audacity"
  description="Remove background noise from audio for free. Audacity's Noise Reduction effect eliminates hiss, hum, fan noise and buzzing. Download free for Windows, Mac & Linux."
  canonical="https://www.audacityteam.org/features/noise-reduction"
>
  <Fragment slot="hero">
    <section id="main" class="bg-gradient-to-r from-indigo-900 to-blue-700">
      <div class="mx-auto px-4 md:px-8 py-4 md:py-8 lg:py-12 max-w-screen-lg">
        <div
          class="flex flex-col md:flex-row md:items-center md:justify-between gap-8 md:gap-12"
        >
          <!-- Left Column - Text Content -->
          <div class="flex flex-col text-center md:text-left md:w-1/2 gap-6">
            <h1
              class="text-xl sm:text-2xl md:text-3xl lg:text-4xl font-semibold text-white leading-tight"
            >
              Remove Background Noise from Audio &ndash; Free Noise Reduction
              Tool
            </h1>
            <p class="text-white text-lg opacity-90">
              Eliminate hiss, hum, fan noise, and buzzing from any recording.
              Free noise reduction for Windows, Mac &amp; Linux.
            </p>

            <div
              class="flex flex-col w-full md:w-fit gap-4 items-center md:items-start pb-2"
            >
              <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
              <noscript>
                <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
              </noscript>
              <DownloadButton client:load />
              <noscript>
                <DownloadButton client:load />
              </noscript>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Right Column - Image -->
          <div class="hidden md:block md:w-1/2">
            <div class="relative">
              <Image
                src={AudacityMockUp}
                alt="A laptop showing the Audacity application"
                width={668}
                quality={80}
                loading="eager"
                class="w-full h-auto"
              />
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <!-- Quick Start Box -->
  <div class="not-prose my-8 rounded-lg border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 p-6">
    <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-blue-900">
      How to remove background noise in Audacity:
    </h3>
    <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-blue-800">
      <li>Select a section containing only background noise</li>
      <li>
        Go to <strong
          >Effect &rarr; Noise Reduction &rarr; Get Noise Profile</strong
        >
      </li>
      <li>Select the audio you want to clean</li>
      <li>Go to <strong>Effect &rarr; Noise Reduction &rarr; OK</strong></li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <h2>How to Remove Background Noise in Audacity</h2>

  <h3>Step 1: Get Noise Profile</h3>
  <p>
    Audacity needs a "noise profile" &ndash; a short sample of pure background
    noise with no speech or music. Find a section in your recording (at least
    0.5 seconds long) where only the unwanted noise is audible. Click and drag
    to select it, then go to <strong
      >Effect &gt; Noise Reduction &gt; Get Noise Profile</strong
    >. Audacity will analyze the noise characteristics and store them for the
    next step.
  </p>

  <h3>Step 2: Apply Noise Reduction</h3>
  <p>
    Now select the audio you want to clean. To process the entire track, press
    <code>Ctrl + A</code> (Windows/Linux) or <code>Cmd + A</code> (Mac). Then open
    <strong>Effect &gt; Noise Reduction</strong> and click <strong>OK</strong> to
    apply reduction using the profile you just captured.
  </p>

  <h3>Step 3: Adjust Settings</h3>
  <p>
    Before clicking OK, fine-tune the Noise Reduction, Sensitivity, and
    Frequency Smoothing sliders to suit your recording. Use the <strong
      >Preview</strong
    > button to hear the effect before committing. If the result sounds unnatural,
    dial back the Noise Reduction value and try again.
  </p>

  <h2>Noise Reduction Settings Explained</h2>

  <h3>Noise Reduction (dB)</h3>
  <p>
    Controls how much of the identified noise is attenuated. Higher values
    remove more noise but can introduce audio artifacts &ndash; a warbling,
    "watery" quality. Values between 6 and 24 dB work well for most recordings.
    Start low and increase until the noise is no longer distracting.
  </p>

  <h3>Sensitivity</h3>
  <p>
    Determines how aggressively Audacity classifies parts of the signal as
    noise. Higher values treat more of the audio as noise to remove. If voices
    or instruments sound muffled after applying, try lowering this value.
  </p>

  <h3>Frequency Smoothing</h3>
  <p>
    Smooths the transition between noise-reduced and untouched frequency bands.
    A value of 3 is a good starting point. Increasing it reduces "musical noise"
    &ndash; the tinny or metallic artifacts that can appear at aggressive
    reduction settings.
  </p>

  <h2>What Types of Noise Can Audacity Remove?</h2>
  <p>
    Audacity's Noise Reduction effect works best on <em>stationary</em> noise &ndash;
    backgrounds that stay roughly constant throughout the recording:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Room hiss / preamp hiss</strong> &ndash; constant low-level hiss from
      microphones or audio interfaces
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Fan noise</strong> &ndash; from computers, air conditioning, or ventilation
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Electrical hum (50/60&nbsp;Hz)</strong> &ndash; caused by ground loops
      or poor cable shielding
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Buzzing</strong> &ndash; from fluorescent lights or other electrical
      interference
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Tape hiss</strong> &ndash; when digitizing old cassette or reel-to-reel
      recordings
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    For non-stationary noise such as traffic, crowd chatter, or background
    music, other tools and techniques will typically be more effective.
  </p>

  <h2>Tips for Best Results</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Select a noise sample that is <strong>at least 0.5 seconds long</strong> and
      contains no intentional audio.
    </li>
    <li>
      Start with moderate settings &ndash; try <strong
        >Noise Reduction: 12&nbsp;dB, Sensitivity: 6, Frequency Smoothing: 3</strong
      > &ndash; and adjust from there.
    </li>
    <li>
      Always use <strong>Preview</strong> before applying to compare processed and
      original audio side-by-side.
    </li>
    <li>
      If audio sounds "watery" or distorted, lower the Noise Reduction value or
      Sensitivity.
    </li>
    <li>
      Record in the quietest environment possible &ndash; noise reduction
      improves recordings but cannot fully substitute for good recording
      conditions.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Alternative Noise Reduction Techniques</h2>
  <p>
    When the standard Noise Reduction effect is not enough, Audacity offers
    additional tools:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Noise Gate</strong> &ndash; Silences audio that falls below a set volume
      threshold, useful for eliminating noise between speech or musical phrases. Found
      under <strong>Effect &gt; Gate</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Spectral Editing</strong> &ndash; Switch to Spectrogram view to visually
      identify and surgically remove specific noise frequencies. Right-click a track
      header and select <strong>Spectrogram</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Equalization</strong> &ndash; Use the Filter Curve EQ to cut the frequency
      range where noise is most prominent without affecting the rest of the audio.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>MuseHub plugins</strong> &ndash; The MuseHub platform offers additional
      noise reduction and audio restoration plug-ins that integrate directly with
      Audacity.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <!-- Why Audacity Box -->
  <div
    class="not-prose my-8 rounded-lg border border-green-200 bg-green-50 p-6"
  >
    <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold text-green-900">
      Why choose Audacity for noise reduction?
    </h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
      <li>&#10003; 100% free and open source</li>
      <li>&#10003; No subscription required</li>
      <li>&#10003; Works offline</li>
      <li>&#10003; Professional-quality results</li>
      <li>&#10003; Windows, Mac &amp; Linux</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Download Audacity Free</h2>
  <p>
    Ready to clean up your recordings? Download Audacity for free on Windows,
    macOS, or Linux and start removing background noise today.
  </p>
  <div
    class="not-prose mt-8 flex flex-col w-full md:w-fit gap-4 items-center sm:items-start text-left"
  >
    <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
    <noscript>
      <DownloadMuseHubButton client:load />
    </noscript>
    <DownloadButton client:load />
    <noscript>
      <DownloadButton client:load />
    </noscript>
  </div>
</FeaturePageLayout>
